r | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 41.\n| {{flagicon|ROM}} Deltacons Tulcea\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n| align=center | 42.\n| {{flagicon|NED}} [[Ortec Nesselande]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 43.\n| {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Noliko Maaseik]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n| align=center | 44.\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Iskra Odintsovo|Iskra Odintsovo]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 45.\n| {{flagicon|POL}} [[ZAKSA K\u0119dzierzyn-Ko\u017ale]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n| align=center | 46.\n| {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 47.\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Top Volley Latina|Andreoli Latina]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n| align=center | 48.\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} Guberniya Nizhniy Novgorod\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 49.\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Gazprom-Ugra Surgut|Gazprom-Yugra]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n| align=center | 50.\n| {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Ziraat Bankas\u0131 Ankara]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n| align=center | 51.\n| {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's volleyball)|Galatasaray SK]]\n| align=center | \n| align=center | '''1'''\n|\n|}\n\n==Titles by country==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Country\n! Won\n! Runner-up\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left| {{ITA}} || 19 || 11 || 30 \n|-\n| 2 ||align=left| {{URS}} || 7 || 2 || 9 \n|-\n| 3 ||align=left| {{RUS}} || 4 || 4 || 8\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left| {{FRA}} || 4 || 1 || 5 \n|-\n| 5 ||align=left| {{GRC}} || 2 || 4 || 6 \n|-\n| 6 ||align=left| {{TCH}} || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 7 ||align=left| {{BGR}} || 1 || 6 || 7 \n|-\n| 8 ||align=left| {{ROU}} || 1 || 4 || 5 \n|-\n| 9 ||align=left| {{TUR}} || 1 || 2 || 3 \n|-\n|rowspan=5| 10 ||align=left| {{NED}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{BEL}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{POR}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{GER}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{UKR}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n| 15 ||align=left| {{SLO}} || 1 || \u2013 || 1 \n|-\n| 16 ||align=left| {{POL}} || \u2013 || 3 || 3 \n|-\n| 17 ||align=left| {{ESP}} || \u2013 || 3 || 3\n|-\n| 18 ||align=left| {{HUN}} || \u2013 || 1 || 1 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cev.eu CEV Website]\n*[https://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/History.aspx?ID=1194 History of the Competition]\n\n{{CEV Cup seasons}}\n{{European Volleyball Competitions}}\n{{Professional Volleyball Leagues}}\n{{European Club Competitions}}\n{{International volleyball}}\n\n[[Category:Men's CEV Cup| ]]\n[[Category:European men's volleyball club competitions]]\n[[Category:European volleyball records and statistics]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CEV_Cup"}
{"title_page": "SMC3", "text_new": "[[File:Structure of the SMC3 (blue)-RAD21 (green) interface (PDB 4UX3).png|thumb|Structure of the interface between SMC3 (blue) and RAD21 (green) (PDB 4UX3) from budding yeast (Gligoris et al. 2014)]]\n{{Infobox_gene}}\n'''Structural maintenance of chromosomes protein 3''' (SMC3) is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the '''SMC3''' [[gene]].<ref name=\"entrez\">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: SMC3 structural maintenance of chromosomes 3| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=9126| accessdate = }}</ref> SMC3 is a subunit of the [[Cohesin]] complex which mediates [[Establishment of sister chromatid cohesion|sister chromatid cohesion]], homologous recombination and [[Topologically associating domain|DNA looping]]. Cohesin is formed of SMC3, [[SMC1A|SMC1]], [[RAD21]] and either [[STAG1|SA1]] or [[STAG2|SA2]]. In humans, SMC3 is present in all cohesin complexes whereas there are multiple [[Sequence homology|paralogs]] for the other subunits.\n\nSMC3 is a member of the  [[SMC protein|SMC protein family]]. Members of this family are key regulators of DNA repair, chromosome condensation and chromosome segregation.\n\n== Structure and interactions ==\nThe domain organisation of SMC proteins is evolutionarily conserved and is composed of an N-terminal [[Walker motifs|Walker A motif]], coiled-coil, \"hinge\", coiled-coil and a C-terminal [[Walker motifs|Walker B motif]]. The protein folds back on itself to form a rod-shaped molecule with a heterodimerisation \"hinge\" domain at one end  and an [[ATP-binding cassette transporter|ABC-type ATPase]] \"head\" at the other. These globular domains are separated by a ~50 nm anti-parallel coiled-coil. SMC3 and SMC1 bind via their hinge domains creating V-shaped heterodimers. The N-terminal domain of RAD21 binds to the coiled coil of SMC3 just above the head domain while the C-terminal domain of RAD21 binds the head domain of SMC1. This end to end binding of the SMC3-SMC1-RAD21 trimer creates a closed ring within which DNA can be entrapped. SA1 or \n\nWhen DNA is replicated and sister chromatid cohesion is established SMC3 is acetylated on a pair of highly conserved lysines by [[ESCO1]] and [[ESCO2]]. In budding yeast this modification is sufficient to stabilise cohesin on the DNA until mitosis but in animals, binding of sororin is also required.\n\nDuring [[meiosis]], SMC3 forms cohesin complexes with [[SMC1B|SMC1\u00df]], [[STAG3 (gene)|STAG3]] and [[REC8]] which generate cohesion between homologous chromosomes and sister chromatids.<ref name=\"pmid20634189\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Garcia-Cruz R, Brie\u00f1o MA, Roig I, Grossmann M, Velilla E, Pujol A, Cabero L, Pessarrodona A, Barbero JL, Garcia Cald\u00e9s M |title=Dynamics of cohesin proteins REC8, STAG3, SMC1 beta and SMC3 are consistent with a role in sister chromatid cohesion during meiosis in human oocytes |journal=Hum. Reprod. |volume=25 |issue=9 |pages=2316\u201327 |year=2010 |pmid=20634189 |doi=10.1093/humrep/deq180 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== Cornelia de Lange syndrome ==\n\n[[Cornelia de Lange syndrome|Cornelia de Lange syndrome (CdLS)]] is a rare genetic disorder that presents with variable clinical abnormalities including [[dysmorphic feature]]s, severe growth retardation, [[global developmental delay]], and [[intellectual disability]].  SMC3 is one of five genes that have been implicated in CdLS.<ref name=\"pmid28781842\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Infante E, Alkorta-Aranburu G, El-Gharbawy A |title=Rare form of autosomal dominant familial Cornelia de Lange syndrome due to a novel duplication in SMC3 |journal=Clin Case Rep |volume=5 |issue=8 |pages=1277\u20131283 |year=2017 |pmid=28781842 |pmc=5538066 |doi=10.1002/ccr3.1010 |url=}}</ref>  In one case report, a novel SMC3 gene duplication was detected in a child with [[failure to thrive]], [[hypotonia]] and facial [[dysmorphic feature]]s of CdLS.<ref name=\"pmid28781842\" />  The same duplication was also observed in the mother, who had milder dysmorphic facies.\n\n==Mouse Model==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"float: right;\" |\n|+ ''Smc3'' knockout mouse phenotype\n|-\n! Characteristic!! Phenotype\n\n|-\n| [[Homozygote]] viability || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| [[Recessive]] lethal study || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| Homozygous Fertility || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| Body weight || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"Body weight\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/weight-curves/ |title=Body weight data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Open Field (animal test)|Anxiety]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Neurological assessment || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Grip strength || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Hot plate test|Hot plate]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Dysmorphology]] || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"Dysmorphology\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/dysmorphology/ |title=Dysmorphology data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Indirect calorimetry]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Glucose tolerance test]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Auditory brainstem response]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry|DEXA]] || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"DEXA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/body-composition-dexa/ |title=DEXA data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Radiography]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Body temperature || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Eye morphology || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Clinical chemistry]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Haematology]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Peripheral blood lymphocyte]]s || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Heart weight || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Eye Histopathology || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| ''[[Salmonella]]'' infection || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal<ref name=\"''Salmonella'' infection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/salmonella-challenge/ |title=''Salmonella'' infection data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Citrobacter]]'' infection || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal<ref name=\"''Citrobacter'' infection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/citrobacter-challenge/ |title=''Citrobacter'' infection data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=2; style=\"text-align: center;\" | All tests and analysis from<ref name=\"mgp_reference\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1755-3768.2010.4142.x | title = The Sanger Mouse Genetics Programme: High throughput characterisation of knockout mice | year = 2010 | author = Gerdin AK | journal = Acta Ophthalmologica | volume = 88 | pages =  925\u20137 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/ Mouse Resources Portal], Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute.</ref>\n|}\n[[Model organism]]s have been used in the study of SMC3 function. A conditional [[knockout mouse]] line, called ''Smc3<sup>tm1a(EUCOMM)Wtsi</sup>''<ref name=\"allele_ref\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knockoutmouse.org/martsearch/search?query=Smc3 |title=International Knockout Mouse Consortium}}</ref><ref name=\"mgi_allele_ref\">{{cite web |url=http://www.informatics.jax.org/searchtool/Search.do?query=MGI:4434007 |title=Mouse Genome Informatics}}</ref> was generated as part of the [[International Knockout Mouse Consortium]] program \u2014 a high-throughput mutagenesis project to generate and distribute animal models of disease to interested scientists.<ref name=\"pmid21677750\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Skarnes WC, Rosen B, West AP, Koutsourakis M, Bushell W, Iyer V, Mujica AO, Thomas M, Harrow J, Cox T, Jackson D, Severin J, Biggs P, Fu J, Nefedov M, de Jong PJ, Stewart AF, Bradley A | title = A conditional knockout resource for the genome-wide study of mouse gene function | journal = Nature | volume = 474 | issue = 7351 | pages = 337\u201342 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21677750 | pmc = 3572410 | doi = 10.1038/nature10163 }}</ref><ref name=\"mouse_library\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dolgin E | title = Mouse library set to be knockout | journal = Nature | volume = 474 | issue = 7351 | pages = 262\u20133 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21677718 | doi = 10.1038/474262a | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"mouse_for_all_reasons\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Collins FS, Rossant J, Wurst W | title = A mouse for all reasons | journal = Cell | volume = 128 | issue = 1 | pages = 9\u201313 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17218247 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2006.12.018 }}</ref>\n\nMale and female animals underwent a standardized [[phenotypic screen]] to determine the effects of deletion.<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /><ref name=\"pmid21722353\">{{cite journal | vauthors = van der Weyden L, White JK, Adams DJ, Logan DW | title = The mouse genetics toolkit: revealing function and mechanism | journal = Genome Biol. | volume = 12 | issue = 6 | pages = 224 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21722353 | pmc = 3218837 | doi = 10.1186/gb-2011-12-6-224 }}</ref> Twenty two tests were carried out on [[mutant]] mice and six significant abnormalities were observed.<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /> No [[homozygous]] [[mutant]] embryos were identified during gestation, and thus none survived until [[weaning]]. The remaining tests were carried out on [[heterozygous]] mutant adult mice. Females had a higher than normal incidence of pre-wean death in their offspring, and also had a decreased body weight. Males heterozygotes displayed a shortened, upturned [[snout]].<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /><ref name=\"pmid21722353\"/>\n\n== Role in Basement Membrane ==\n\nSMC3 occurs in certain cell types as a secreted protein and post-translational addition of [[chondroitin sulfate]] chains gives rise to the secreted [[proteoglycan]] '''bamacan''', an abundant [[basement membrane]] protein.<ref name=\"entrez\" />\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bookshelf/br.fcgi?book=gene&part=cdls  GeneReviews/NCBI/UW/NIH entry on Cornelia de Lange syndrome]\n* {{FactorBook|SMC3}}\n\n{{proteoglycans}}\n{{Nucleus}}\n\n[[Category:Human proteins]]\n[[Category:Genes mutated in mice]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox_gene}}\n'''Structural maintenance of chromosomes protein 3''' (SMC3) is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the '''SMC3''' [[gene]].<ref name=\"entrez\">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: SMC3 structural maintenance of chromosomes 3| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=9126| accessdate = }}</ref> SMC3 is a subunit of the [[Cohesin]] complex which mediates [[Establishment of sister chromatid cohesion|sister chromatid cohesion]], homologous recombination and [[Topologically associating domain|DNA looping]]. Cohesin is formed of SMC3, [[SMC1A|SMC1]], [[RAD21]] and either [[STAG1|SA1]] or [[STAG2|SA2]]. In humans, SMC3 is present in all cohesin complexes whereas there are multiple [[Sequence homology|paralogs]] for the other subunits.\n\nSMC3 is a member of the  [[SMC protein|SMC protein family]]. Members of this family are key regulators of DNA repair, chromosome condensation and chromosome segregation.\n\n== Structure and interactions ==\nThe domain organisation of SMC proteins is evolutionarily conserved and is composed of an N-terminal [[Walker motifs|Walker A motif]], coiled-coil, \"hinge\", coiled-coil and a C-terminal [[Walker motifs|Walker B motif]]. The protein folds back on itself to form a rod-shaped molecule with a heterodimerisation \"hinge\" domain at one end  and an [[ATP-binding cassette transporter|ABC-type ATPase]] \"head\" at the other. These globular domains are separated by a ~50 nm anti-parallel coiled-coil. SMC3 and SMC1 bind via their hinge domains creating V-shaped heterodimers. The N-terminal domain of RAD21 binds to the coiled coil of SMC3 just above the head domain while the C-terminal domain of RAD21 binds the head domain of SMC1. This end to end binding of the SMC3-SMC1-RAD21 trimer creates a closed ring within which DNA can be entrapped. SA1 or \n\nWhen DNA is replicated and sister chromatid cohesion is established SMC3 is acetylated on a pair of highly conserved lysines by [[ESCO1]] and [[ESCO2]]. In budding yeast this modification is sufficient to stabilise cohesin on the DNA until mitosis but in animals, binding of sororin is also required.\n\nDuring [[meiosis]], SMC3 forms cohesin complexes with [[SMC1B|SMC1\u00df]], [[STAG3 (gene)|STAG3]] and [[REC8]] which generate cohesion between homologous chromosomes and sister chromatids.<ref name=\"pmid20634189\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Garcia-Cruz R, Brie\u00f1o MA, Roig I, Grossmann M, Velilla E, Pujol A, Cabero L, Pessarrodona A, Barbero JL, Garcia Cald\u00e9s M |title=Dynamics of cohesin proteins REC8, STAG3, SMC1 beta and SMC3 are consistent with a role in sister chromatid cohesion during meiosis in human oocytes |journal=Hum. Reprod. |volume=25 |issue=9 |pages=2316\u201327 |year=2010 |pmid=20634189 |doi=10.1093/humrep/deq180 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== Cornelia de Lange syndrome ==\n\n[[Cornelia de Lange syndrome|Cornelia de Lange syndrome (CdLS)]] is a rare genetic disorder that presents with variable clinical abnormalities including [[dysmorphic feature]]s, severe growth retardation, [[global developmental delay]], and [[intellectual disability]].  SMC3 is one of five genes that have been implicated in CdLS.<ref name=\"pmid28781842\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Infante E, Alkorta-Aranburu G, El-Gharbawy A |title=Rare form of autosomal dominant familial Cornelia de Lange syndrome due to a novel duplication in SMC3 |journal=Clin Case Rep |volume=5 |issue=8 |pages=1277\u20131283 |year=2017 |pmid=28781842 |pmc=5538066 |doi=10.1002/ccr3.1010 |url=}}</ref>  In one case report, a novel SMC3 gene duplication was detected in a child with [[failure to thrive]], [[hypotonia]] and facial [[dysmorphic feature]]s of CdLS.<ref name=\"pmid28781842\" />  The same duplication was also observed in the mother, who had milder dysmorphic facies.\n\n==Mouse Model==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"float: right;\" |\n|+ ''Smc3'' knockout mouse phenotype\n|-\n! Characteristic!! Phenotype\n\n|-\n| [[Homozygote]] viability || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| [[Recessive]] lethal study || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| Homozygous Fertility || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal\n|-\n| Body weight || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"Body weight\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/weight-curves/ |title=Body weight data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Open Field (animal test)|Anxiety]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Neurological assessment || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Grip strength || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Hot plate test|Hot plate]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Dysmorphology]] || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"Dysmorphology\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/dysmorphology/ |title=Dysmorphology data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Indirect calorimetry]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Glucose tolerance test]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Auditory brainstem response]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry|DEXA]] || bgcolor=\"#C40000\"|Abnormal<ref name=\"DEXA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/body-composition-dexa/ |title=DEXA data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Radiography]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Body temperature || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Eye morphology || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Clinical chemistry]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Haematology]] || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| [[Peripheral blood lymphocyte]]s || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Heart weight || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| Eye Histopathology || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal\n|-\n| ''[[Salmonella]]'' infection || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal<ref name=\"''Salmonella'' infection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/salmonella-challenge/ |title=''Salmonella'' infection data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Citrobacter]]'' infection || bgcolor=\"#488ED3\"|Normal<ref name=\"''Citrobacter'' infection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/phenotyping/MBBZ/citrobacter-challenge/ |title=''Citrobacter'' infection data for Smc3 |publisher=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=2; style=\"text-align: center;\" | All tests and analysis from<ref name=\"mgp_reference\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1755-3768.2010.4142.x | title = The Sanger Mouse Genetics Programme: High throughput characterisation of knockout mice | year = 2010 | author = Gerdin AK | journal = Acta Ophthalmologica | volume = 88 | pages =  925\u20137 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sanger.ac.uk/mouseportal/ Mouse Resources Portal], Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute.</ref>\n|}\n[[Model organism]]s have been used in the study of SMC3 function. A conditional [[knockout mouse]] line, called ''Smc3<sup>tm1a(EUCOMM)Wtsi</sup>''<ref name=\"allele_ref\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knockoutmouse.org/martsearch/search?query=Smc3 |title=International Knockout Mouse Consortium}}</ref><ref name=\"mgi_allele_ref\">{{cite web |url=http://www.informatics.jax.org/searchtool/Search.do?query=MGI:4434007 |title=Mouse Genome Informatics}}</ref> was generated as part of the [[International Knockout Mouse Consortium]] program \u2014 a high-throughput mutagenesis project to generate and distribute animal models of disease to interested scientists.<ref name=\"pmid21677750\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Skarnes WC, Rosen B, West AP, Koutsourakis M, Bushell W, Iyer V, Mujica AO, Thomas M, Harrow J, Cox T, Jackson D, Severin J, Biggs P, Fu J, Nefedov M, de Jong PJ, Stewart AF, Bradley A | title = A conditional knockout resource for the genome-wide study of mouse gene function | journal = Nature | volume = 474 | issue = 7351 | pages = 337\u201342 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21677750 | pmc = 3572410 | doi = 10.1038/nature10163 }}</ref><ref name=\"mouse_library\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dolgin E | title = Mouse library set to be knockout | journal = Nature | volume = 474 | issue = 7351 | pages = 262\u20133 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21677718 | doi = 10.1038/474262a | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"mouse_for_all_reasons\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Collins FS, Rossant J, Wurst W | title = A mouse for all reasons | journal = Cell | volume = 128 | issue = 1 | pages = 9\u201313 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17218247 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2006.12.018 }}</ref>\n\nMale and female animals underwent a standardized [[phenotypic screen]] to determine the effects of deletion.<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /><ref name=\"pmid21722353\">{{cite journal | vauthors = van der Weyden L, White JK, Adams DJ, Logan DW | title = The mouse genetics toolkit: revealing function and mechanism | journal = Genome Biol. | volume = 12 | issue = 6 | pages = 224 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21722353 | pmc = 3218837 | doi = 10.1186/gb-2011-12-6-224 }}</ref> Twenty two tests were carried out on [[mutant]] mice and six significant abnormalities were observed.<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /> No [[homozygous]] [[mutant]] embryos were identified during gestation, and thus none survived until [[weaning]]. The remaining tests were carried out on [[heterozygous]] mutant adult mice. Females had a higher than normal incidence of pre-wean death in their offspring, and also had a decreased body weight. Males heterozygotes displayed a shortened, upturned [[snout]].<ref name=\"mgp_reference\" /><ref name=\"pmid21722353\"/>\n\n== Role in Basement Membrane ==\n\nSMC3 occurs in certain cell types as a secreted protein and post-translational addition of [[chondroitin sulfate]] chains gives rise to the secreted [[proteoglycan]] '''bamacan''', an abundant [[basement membrane]] protein.<ref name=\"entrez\" />\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bookshelf/br.fcgi?book=gene&part=cdls  GeneReviews/NCBI/UW/NIH entry on Cornelia de Lange syndrome]\n* {{FactorBook|SMC3}}\n\n{{proteoglycans}}\n{{Nucleus}}\n\n[[Category:Human proteins]]\n[[Category:Genes mutated in mice]]\n", "name_user": "Jimcricket90", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SMC3"}
{"title_page": "Sydney MacEwan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =  Sydney MacEWAN \n| image       =  Sydney MacEwan.png \n| caption     =  Sydney Alfred MacEwan \n| birth_date  =  {{birth date|df=yes|1908|10|19}} \n| birth_place =  [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] \n| death_date  =  {{death date and age|df=yes|1991|9|25|1908|10|19}}\n| occupation  =  Priest, professional singer \n}}\nCanon '''Sydney Alfred MacEwan''' (19 October 1908{{spaced ndash}}25 September 1991)<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/canon-sydney-macewan-1.503112 ''Herald Scotland'', 26 September 1991]</ref> was a Scottish [[tenor]], who sang traditional Scottish and Irish songs.<ref>[http://www.footstompin.com/artists/father_sydney_macewan \"Foot Stompin' Celtic Music\"], footstompin.com; accessed 10 August 2014.</ref>  His name has also been recorded as Alfred Sydney Marley MacEwan.\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early life==\n\nMacEwan was born and brought up in the [[Springburn]] area of [[Glasgow]] by his mother alone, after his father left the family. Sydney was the younger of two brothers. His mother was Irish, from the [[Portadown]] area, [[County Armagh]], and his father was born in [[Partick]]. The family were poor but Sydney's mother managed to pay for music lessons for both her sons and both won bursaries to good schools. Sydney attended [[St. Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St Aloysius' College]] in Garnethill from 1919 to 1924, before transferring to [[Hillhead]] Academy. He also commenced his singing career.\n\nIn 1938 MacEwan retired from concert work, and during World War II was an ambulance driver and an [[RAF]] [[chaplain]].<ref name=Age1948>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article206871912 |title=Singing Priest Likes Crooner |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=29018 |location=Victoria |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  He was ordained in 1944.\n\n==Catholic priesthood==\n\nAt the age of 18, Sydney MacEwan entered training to become a Jesuit priest at [[Parkstead House|Manresa House]] in [[Roehampton]], London, but left after a deeply unsatisfactory first term. He chose to study at [[Glasgow University]] instead. He completed a Master of Arts degree at the university.\n\nThroughout his life MacEwan had retained a deep love of the Catholic Church and, despite his earlier experience with the Jesuits, chose to abandon his fame and success as a world-famous tenor, to enter the [[Bearsden]] [[Seminary]] in Glasgow before going to [[The Scots College (Rome)|Pontifical Scots College]] in Rome, to follow his vocation to become a priest. He was [[ordination|ordained]] in [[St Andrew's Cathedral, Glasgow]] in 1944<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article225966164 |title=CLERIC TENOR IN AUSTRALIA |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4114 |location=Victoria |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146493024 |title=Ordination Of Sydney McEwan |newspaper=[[Catholic Weekly]] |volume=III |issue=120 |location=New South Wales |date=15 June 1944 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and celebrated his first Mass at [[St Aloysius' Church, Glasgow|St Aloysius' Church]].\n\nCombining priesthood and music, he undertook tours of North America and Australia, where those concerts helping to provide funding for the building of [[St Columba's Cathedral]] in [[Oban]]. He helped with funds to renovate the  Church of St Margaret's in [[Lochgilphead]], in Argyll,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article172510028 |title=Father Sydney McEwan Now Parish Priest |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Melbourne)|The Advocate]] |volume=LXXXIII |issue=4937 |location=Victoria |date=9 March 1950 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100161241 |title=PRIEST WHO SANG TO REBUILD HIS CHURCH |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=New South Wales |date=18 July 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=3 (Daily and Evening) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> where he was parish priest for 17 years.\n\nIn the Scottish summer of 1947, MacEwan arranged for Australian and New Zealand food parcels which he distributed around the parish:  \n:If these good people could see the poor wee bairns enjoying the contents of the parcels, they would be well rewarded for their great kindness. \"It is so heartening to feel that the poor old Mother is being helped in her distress by her young and vigorous children. They have been superb in their charity. God love them all.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article172488751 |title=THANKS FOR FOOD PARCELS |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Melbourne)|The Advocate]] |volume=LXXX |issue=4795 |location=Victoria |date=25 June 1947 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in 1948 the jovial clergyman and singer said: \n:Of the two, I think I prefer a concert audience to a congregation. People listen to me more attentively in a concert than in a church.<ref name=Age1948 />\n\nHowever it was quite clear his performances were to fund and secondary to his religious duties, where after ordination he decreed all concert earnings went to charities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article220746207 |title=MAY VISIT LITHGOW |newspaper=[[Lithgow Mercury]] |location=New South Wales |date=29 August 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5|edition=CITY |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  MacEwan also rejected the title of a 'singing priest'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161364891 |title=SCOTCH TENOR |newspaper=[[The National Advocate]] |location=New South Wales |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter Lochgilphead, he moved to St Andrew's Church in [[Rothesay, Bute|Rothesay]]. A stained glass window in the church in [[Lochgilphead]] is dedicated to the MacEwan family. His parishioners became accustomed to his concert tours, and enjoyed his return each time.<ref name=Columbia1950>Columbia (Australia) music record 330S 1073, c. 1950, cover notes.</ref>\n\nIn 1977 he was narrowly defeated in the election for [[Lord Rector]] of the [[University of Glasgow]]. He spent his later years as retired priest, assisting when necessary at Our Lady and St Mun's church in [[Dunoon]].{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Singing career==\n\nAged 12, his brother entered him into an end-of-the-pier talent show in [[Dunoon]]. Come the Grand Final of the contest at the end of the summer, Sydney was the clear winner, receiving a prize of five shillings and half a crown. {{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nWhile at university, his vocal talents were noticed and he began a singing career on the advice of Sir [[Compton Mackenzie]] and Irish tenor [[John McCormack (tenor)|John McCormack]]. At this time he came to the attention of the Scottish region of the [[British Broadcasting Company]], and became heavily involved in many broadcasts, specifically the ''Children's Hour'' programme.<ref name=Columbia1950 />\n\nHe began recording for [[Parlophone]] in 1934 while still attending the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London and being tutored by [[Harry Plunket Greene|Plunket Greene]].<ref name=Columbia1950 />\n\nHe toured in 1936, playing to audiences in Canada, the United States of America, New Zealand, and Australia,<ref name=Bowen1948>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article203169696 |title=FAMOUS SINGER |newspaper=[[Bowen Independent]] |volume=45 |issue=4263 |location=Queensland |date=23 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  and the tour was repeated in 1938.\n\nStill performing as a priest, MacEwan nonetheless continued to record and tour. Further trips to North America and Australia took place until as late as 1956.  At one time he indicated a liking for the style of American crooner [[Bing Crosby]].<ref name=Age1948 />\n\n===Australian tours===\n\nMacEwan's 1936 tour of Australia went as far north as [[Townsville]].<ref name=Bowen1948 />\n\nCommencing the 1948 tour in April, MacEwan attended Saint Mary's Cathedral in Sydney. Before Cardinal [[Francis Spellman]], Archbishop of New York, he celebrated a mass for peace, singing the liturgy there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46906013 |title=SYDNEY McEWAN RECITES |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |volume=64 |issue=19,276 |location=Western Australia |date=27 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103725672 |title=MASS CELEBRATED BY FATHER McEWAN |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=New South Wales |date=30 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 (Daily and Evening) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  Arriving in Australia by [[flying boat]], he took the mail train firstly to Melbourne as part of the Centenary of the Catholic Church celebrations.<ref name=Bowen1948 />  Normally his musical public performances were limited towards charitable causes. The tour was with the [[Australian Broadcasting Commission]], with six public performances and eighteen studio recitals in Sydney, Brisbane, Adelaide, Canberra, and Melbourne.  He travelled as far as the town of [[Bowen, Queensland]], to see North Queensland and to 'have a surf before the winter set in',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18069060 |title=Left Plane To Have A Surf |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=34,427 |date=24 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> delivering a benediction to a large congregation there.<ref name=Bowen1948 />\n\nMacEwan's June to October 1951 Australian tour included concerts in Western Australia.  Arriving by sea on the ''[[SS Oronsay (1950)|SS Oransay]]'' in mid-June, he struck down with influenza and was unable to perform in that State and also at Adelaide.<ref name=Illawarra1951>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article135798774 |title=Father McEwan [?] |newspaper=[[Illawarra Daily Mercury]] |location=New South Wales |date=5 September 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  It was considered he would be unable to fulfil any singing obligations for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140331715 |title=Scottish Tenor's Good Recovery |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=23,387 |location=New South Wales |date=17 September 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  The money of 'thousands of pounds' raised was going to build the memorial chapel at the [[St Columba's Cathedral|Oban Catholic Cathedral]], 'be dedicated to the Scottish and Australian soldiers who fell in the Second World War'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224479826 |title=SINGING PRIEST PRAISES VOICES |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4294 |location=Victoria |date=10 October 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  At the time his Melbourne attendance with the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] was also the highest paid fee for a visiting singer.\n\n==Later years==\n\nHe was featured on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|This Is Your Life]]'' programme in October 1962 and his autobiography, ''On the High C's'', was published in 1973.\n\nSydney MacEwan died in September 1991, aged 82. His funeral was held in St Andrew's Cathedral, the church where he was ordained. He was survived by a brother.\n\nIn Ireland on the first day of May each year, the popular hymn \u2018'Bring flowers of the rarest\u2019', also known as \u2018'Queen of the May\u2019', sung by MacEwan is played over the radio.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'KELLY|first1=Sheila|title=Canon Sydney MacEwan|url=https://www.irelandsown.ie/canon-sydney-mcewan|publisher=Ireland's Own|accessdate=1 December 2017|date=21 Apr 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\nMacEwan's tenor voice was captured in 39 [[Phonograph record|record]] albums, singles, and [[Extended play|EPs]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Father Sydney MacEwan|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1420586-Father-Sydney-MacEwan|website=Discogs|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=1 December 2017|date=2010}}</ref>  It includes:\n\n* ''Songs of Scotland and Ireland'', sung by Father Sydney MacEwan with orchestra conducted by Philip Green.  The Columbia record (330S 1073) was recorded in Australia circ 1950.  The rear cover note was written by Mervyn Douglas.  Side 1 songs were Scotland the brave, My ain folk, Bonnie Mary of Argylle, The road to the Isles, and Loch Lomond.  Side 2 songs were The star of County Down, Mother Machree, Killarney in the Spring, The youth of the heart, and Rose of Killarney.\n\nIn 1956-57 Columbia released his LP \"Christmas Carols\" (CL 924). Neither the organist nor the choir who accompany him are identified in the liner notes. The album includes a rendition of Michael Head's \"The Three Mummers\" (a modern carol recently recorded by [[Anne Sofie von Otter]] and Bengt Forsberg).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/101057031/ Profile], ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''; accessed 10 August 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bigredbook.info/sydney_macewan.html Sydney MacEwan's appearance on ''This Is Your Life''], bigredbook.info; accessed 10 August 2014.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macewan, Sydney}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish people of Irish descent]] <!-- on mother's side -->\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Aloysius' College, Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish tenors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Springburn]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People from Lochgilphead]]\n[[Category:People from Rothesay, Bute]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =  Sydney MacEWAN \n| image       =  Sydney MacEwan.png \n| caption     =  Sydney Alfred MacEwan \n| birth_date  =  {{birth date|df=yes|1908|10|19}} \n| birth_place =  [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] \n| death_date  =  {{death date and age|df=yes|1991|9|25|1908|10|19}}\n| occupation  =  Priest, professional singer \n}}\nCanon '''Sydney Alfred MacEwan''' (19 October 1908{{spaced ndash}}25 September 1991)<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/canon-sydney-macewan-1.503112 ''Herald Scotland'', 26 September 1991]</ref> was a Scottish [[tenor]], who sang traditional Scottish and Irish songs.<ref>[http://www.footstompin.com/artists/father_sydney_macewan \"Foot Stompin' Celtic Music\"], footstompin.com; accessed 10 August 2014.</ref>  His name has also been recorded as Alfred Sydney Marley MacEwan.\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early life==\n\nMacEwan was born and brought up in the [[Springburn]] area of [[Glasgow]] by his mother alone, after his father left the family. Sydney was the younger of two brothers. His mother was Irish, from the [[Portadown]] area, [[County Armagh]], and his father was born in [[Partick]]. The family were poor but Sydney's mother managed to pay for music lessons for both her sons and both won bursaries to good schools. Sydney attended [[St. Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St Aloysius' College]] in Garnethill from 1919 to 1924, before transferring to [[Hillhead]] Academy. He also commenced his singing career.\n\nIn 1938 MacEwan retired from concert work, and during World War II was an ambulance driver and an [[RAF]] [[chaplain]].<ref name=Age1948>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article206871912 |title=Singing Priest Likes Crooner |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=29018 |location=Victoria |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  He was ordained in 1944.\n\n==Catholic priesthood==\n\nAt the age of 18, Sydney MacEwan entered training to become a Jesuit priest at [[Parkstead House|Manresa House]] in [[Roehampton]], London, but left after a deeply unsatisfactory first term. He chose to study at [[Glasgow University]] instead. He completed a Master of Arts degree at the university.\n\nThroughout his life MacEwan had retained a deep love of the Catholic Church and, despite his earlier experience with the Jesuits, chose to abandon his fame and success as a world-famous tenor, to enter the [[Bearsden]] [[Seminary]] in Glasgow before going to [[The Scots College (Rome)|Pontifical Scots College]] in Rome, to follow his vocation to become a priest. He was [[ordination|ordained]] in [[St Andrew's Cathedral, Glasgow]] in 1944<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article225966164 |title=CLERIC TENOR IN AUSTRALIA |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4114 |location=Victoria |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146493024 |title=Ordination Of Sydney McEwan |newspaper=[[Catholic Weekly]] |volume=III |issue=120 |location=New South Wales |date=15 June 1944 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and celebrated his first Mass at [[St Aloysius' Church, Glasgow|St Aloysius' Church]].\n\nCombining priesthood and music, he undertook tours of North America and Australia, where those concerts helping to provide funding for the building of [[St Columba's Cathedral]] in [[Oban]]. He helped with funds to renovate the  Church of St Margaret's in [[Lochgilphead]], in Argyll,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article172510028 |title=Father Sydney McEwan Now Parish Priest |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Melbourne)|The Advocate]] |volume=LXXXIII |issue=4937 |location=Victoria |date=9 March 1950 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100161241 |title=PRIEST WHO SANG TO REBUILD HIS CHURCH |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=New South Wales |date=18 July 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=3 (Daily and Evening) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> where he was parish priest for 17 years.\n\nIn the Scottish summer of 1947, MacEwan arranged for Australian and New Zealand food parcels which he distributed around the parish:  \n:If these good people could see the poor wee bairns enjoying the contents of the parcels, they would be well rewarded for their great kindness. \"It is so heartening to feel that the poor old Mother is being helped in her distress by her young and vigorous children. They have been superb in their charity. God love them all.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article172488751 |title=THANKS FOR FOOD PARCELS |newspaper=[[The Advocate (Melbourne)|The Advocate]] |volume=LXXX |issue=4795 |location=Victoria |date=25 June 1947 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=28 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in 1948 the jovial clergyman and singer said: \n:Of the two, I think I prefer a concert audience to a congregation. People listen to me more attentively in a concert than in a church.<ref name=Age1948 />\n\nHowever it was quite clear his performances were to fund and secondary to his religious duties, where after ordination he decreed all concert earnings went to charities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article220746207 |title=MAY VISIT LITHGOW |newspaper=[[Lithgow Mercury]] |location=New South Wales |date=29 August 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5|edition=CITY |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  MacEwan also rejected the title of a 'singing priest'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161364891 |title=SCOTCH TENOR |newspaper=[[The National Advocate]] |location=New South Wales |date=28 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter Lochgilphead, he moved to St Andrew's Church in [[Rothesay, Bute|Rothesay]]. A stained glass window in the church in [[Lochgilphead]] is dedicated to the MacEwan family. His parishioners became accustomed to his concert tours, and enjoyed his return each time.<ref name=Columbia1950>Columbia (Australia) music record 330S 1073, c. 1950, cover notes.</ref>\n\nIn 1977 he was narrowly defeated in the election for [[Lord Rector]] of the [[University of Glasgow]]. He spent his later years as retired priest, assisting when necessary at Our Lady and St Mun's church in [[Dunoon]].{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Singing career==\n\nAged 12, his brother entered him into an end-of-the-pier talent show in [[Dunoon]]. Come the Grand Final of the contest at the end of the summer, Sydney was the clear winner, receiving a prize of five shillings and half a crown. {{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nWhile at university, his vocal talents were noticed and he began a singing career on the advice of Sir [[Compton Mackenzie]] and Irish tenor [[John McCormack (tenor)|John McCormack]]. At this time he came to the attention of the Scottish region of the [[British Broadcasting Company]], and became heavily involved in many broadcasts, specifically the ''Children's Hour'' programme.<ref name=Columbia1950 />\n\nHe began recording for [[Parlophone]] in 1934 while still attending the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London and being tutored by [[Harry Plunket Greene|Plunket Greene]].<ref name=Columbia1950 />\n\nHe toured in 1936, playing to audiences in Canada, the United States of America, New Zealand, and Australia,<ref name=Bowen1948>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article203169696 |title=FAMOUS SINGER |newspaper=[[Bowen Independent]] |volume=45 |issue=4263 |location=Queensland |date=23 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  and the tour was repeated in 1938.\n\nStill performing as a priest, MacEwan nonetheless continued to record and tour. Further trips to North America and Australia took place until as late as 1956.  At one time he indicated a liking for the style of American crooner [[Bing Crosby]].<ref name=Age1948 />\n\n===Australian tours===\n\nMacEwan's 1936 tour of Australia went as far north as [[Townsville]].<ref name=Bowen1948 />\n\nCommencing the 1948 tour in April, MacEwan attended Saint Mary's Cathedral in Sydney. Before Cardinal [[Francis Spellman]], Archbishop of New York, he celebrated a mass for peace, singing the liturgy there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46906013 |title=SYDNEY McEWAN RECITES |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |volume=64 |issue=19,276 |location=Western Australia |date=27 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103725672 |title=MASS CELEBRATED BY FATHER McEWAN |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=New South Wales |date=30 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=5 (Daily and Evening) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  Arriving in Australia by [[flying boat]], he took the mail train firstly to Melbourne as part of the Centenary of the Catholic Church celebrations.<ref name=Bowen1948 />  Normally his musical public performances were limited towards charitable causes. The tour was with the [[Australian Broadcasting Commission]], with six public performances and eighteen studio recitals in Sydney, Brisbane, Adelaide, Canberra, and Melbourne.  He travelled as far as the town of [[Bowen, Queensland]], to see North Queensland and to 'have a surf before the winter set in',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18069060 |title=Left Plane To Have A Surf |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=34,427 |date=24 April 1948 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> delivering a benediction to a large congregation there.<ref name=Bowen1948 />\n\nMacEwan's June to October 1951 Australian tour included concerts in Western Australia.  Arriving by sea on the ''[[SS Oronsay (1950)|SS Oransay]]'' in mid-June, he struck down with influenza and was unable to perform in that State and also at Adelaide.<ref name=Illawarra1951>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article135798774 |title=Father McEwan [?] |newspaper=[[Illawarra Daily Mercury]] |location=New South Wales |date=5 September 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  It was considered he would be unable to fulfil any singing obligations for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140331715 |title=Scottish Tenor's Good Recovery |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=23,387 |location=New South Wales |date=17 September 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  The money of 'thousands of pounds' raised was going to build the memorial chapel at the [[St Columba's Cathedral|Oban Catholic Cathedral]], 'be dedicated to the Scottish and Australian soldiers who fell in the Second World War'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224479826 |title=SINGING PRIEST PRAISES VOICES |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4294 |location=Victoria |date=10 October 1951 |accessdate=1 December 2017 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  At the time his Melbourne attendance with the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] was also the highest paid fee for a visiting singer.\n\n==Later years==\n\nHe was featured on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|This Is Your Life]]'' programme in October 1962 and his autobiography, ''On the High C's'', was published in 1973.\n\nSydney MacEwan died in September 1991, aged 82. His funeral was held in St Andrew's Cathedral, the church where he was ordained. He was survived by a brother.\n\nIn Ireland on the first day of May each year, the popular hymn \u2018'Bring flowers of the rarest\u2019', also known as \u2018'Queen of the May\u2019', sung by MacEwan is played over the radio.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'KELLY|first1=Sheila|title=Canon Sydney MacEwan|url=https://www.irelandsown.ie/canon-sydney-mcewan|publisher=Ireland's Own|accessdate=1 December 2017|date=21 Apr 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\nMacEwan's tenor voice was captured in 39 [[Phonograph record|record]] albums, singles, and [[Extended play|EPs]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Father Sydney MacEwan|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1420586-Father-Sydney-MacEwan|website=Discogs|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=1 December 2017|date=2010}}</ref>  It includes:\n\n* ''Songs of Scotland and Ireland'', sung by Father Sydney MacEwan with orchestra conducted by Philip Green.  The Columbia record (330S 1073) was recorded in Australia circ 1950.  The rear cover note was written by Mervyn Douglas.  Side 1 songs were Scotland the brave, My ain folk, Bonnie Mary of Argylle, The road to the Isles, and Loch Lomond.  Side 2 songs were The star of County Down, Mother Machree, Killarney in the Spring, The youth of the heart, and Rose of Killarney.\n\nIn 1956-57 Columbia released his LP \"Christmas Carols\" (CL 924). Neither the organist nor the choir who accompany him are identified in the liner notes. The album includes a rendition of Michael Head's \"The Three Mummers\" (a modern carol recently recorded by [[Anne Sofie von Otter]] and Bengt Forsberg).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/101057031/ Profile], ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''; accessed 10 August 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bigredbook.info/sydney_macewan.html Sydney MacEwan's appearance on ''This Is Your Life''], bigredbook.info; accessed 10 August 2014.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macewan, Sydney}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish people of Irish descent]] <!-- on mother's side -->\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Aloysius' College, Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish tenors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Springburn]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People from Lochgilphead]]\n[[Category:People from Rothesay, Bute]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sydney_MacEwan"}
{"title_page": "Simon Sinek", "text_new": "{{short description|British/American author and motivational speaker}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image = simon sinek.jpg\n| imagesize = 225px\n| name = Simon Sinek\n| pseudonym = \n| caption = Sinek, TEDx Maastricht 2011\n| birth_name = Simon Oliver Sinek\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|10|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Wimbledon, London]], England\n| occupation = Author, [[motivational speaker]]\n| education = \n| alma_mater = City, University of London<br>Brandeis University\n| notableworks = ''[[Start With Why]]: How Great Leaders Inspire Everyone to Take Action'',''[[The Infinite Game]]''\n| years_active = \n| website = {{URL|https://simonsinek.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Simon Oliver Sinek''' (born October 9, 1973)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=gP0Fzj%2Fswk0Ugg9RqxkPXQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=19 July 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> is a British-born American author and [[motivational speaker]]. He is the author of five books, including ''[[Start With Why]]'' (2009)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkauflin/2017/06/20/the-years-5-bestselling-leadership-books-and-why-theyre-so-great/#257bb5043ac0|title=The Year's Five Bestselling Leadership Books, And Why They're So Great|last=Kauflin|first=Jeff|work=Forbes|access-date=January 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and ''[[The Infinite Game]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nSinek was born in [[Wimbledon, London]], United Kingdom and as a child lived in Johannesburg, South Africa, London, and Hong Kong before settling in the United States. He graduated from [[Northern Valley Regional High School at Demarest]] in 1991.<ref name=\"NorthernValleyRegionalHighSchool2013February11NVD\">{{cite web|last1=NVD|first1=|title=Simon Sinek Returns to NVD|url=http://www.nvnet.org/?plugin=RWD&Templates=RWD&object=/superintendents_blog/I074E94AE&infobar=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912182526/http://www.nvnet.org/?plugin=RWD&Templates=RWD&object=/superintendents_blog/I074E94AE&infobar=no |archive-date=12 September 2014 |url-status=dead|accessdate=28 January 2020|agency=NVD|publisher=Northern Valley Regional High School|date=11 February 2013|location=United States|language=English}}</ref> He studied law at London's [[City, University of London|City University]], but left law school to go into advertising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toolshero.com/toolsheroes/simon-sinek/|title=Simon Sinek biography, quotes and books|date=September 29, 2014}}</ref> He received a BA in [[cultural anthropology]] from [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://www.director.co.uk/opinion-simon-sinek-to-grow-your-business-let-go-20674-2/|title=Simon Sinek: To grow your business, let go|last1=Maxwell|first1=Chris|date=Jan 6, 2017|work=Director|accessdate=Jan 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Career==\nSinek began his career at the New York ad agencies [[Havas Worldwide|Euro RSCG]] and [[Ogilvy & Mather]].<ref name=\"Director\" /> He later launched his own business, Sinek Partners.<ref name=\"Director\" />\n\nNow Sinek is an advocate to Social Studies as a way to better understand people and organisation.\n\nAs he was studying [[anthropology]], so he did some woek with the [[Massachusetts Police Association|Massachusetts police]] in order to understand the relation between police and people.In some cases he even took part in some police operations wearing bullet proof jackets to better understand the police work.\n\nHe have even participated in [https://bluecourage.com/ Blue Courage] an organisation that gives training to police.\n[[File:Golden circle.png|thumb|Simon Sinek's golden circle which describes a perspective of the influence of successful leaders and organisations.|alt=]]\nSinek has written five books. ''[[Start With Why]]'', his first book, was published October 2009. His second book, titled ''Leaders Eat Last'', appeared on the bestseller lists of the ''Wall Street Journal'' and ''The New York Times''.<ref name=\"Director\"/>   \n\nAs a motivational speaker, Sinek has given talks at [[United Nations Global Compact|The UN Global Compact]] Leaders Summit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unglobalcompact.org/take-action/events/leaders-summit/leaders-summit-programme|title=Programme {{!}} UN Global Compact|website=www.unglobalcompact.org|access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref> and at the [[TED_(conference)#TEDx|TEDx]] conference.<ref name=\"Entrepreneur\">{{cite news|last1=Koji|first1=David|title=An Inspiring Discussion With Simon Sinek About Learning Your 'Why'|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/284791|accessdate=2017-01-12|publisher=Entrepreneur|date=2016-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, ''[[The Young Turks]]'' reported a $98,000 no-bid contract from [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) for \"customized Simon Sinek leadership training\" to take place between April 26 and May 15 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tytnetwork.com/2018/06/26/ice-paid-famous-motivational-speaker-for-leadership-training/|title=ICE Paid Famous Motivational Speaker for 'Leadership Training'|website=tytnetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref>\n\nSinek is also an instructor of strategic communications at Columbia University,<ref>{{cite web |title=Instructor Simon Sinek Featured by 99% {{!}} Columbia University School of Professional Studies |url=http://sps.columbia.edu/strategic-communications/news/instructor-simon-sinek-featured-99 |website=sps.columbia.edu |language=en}}</ref> and is an adjunct staff member of the [[RAND Corporation]].<ref name=\"RAND\">{{cite web |title=RAND Corporation Staff Directory |url=https://www.rand.org/about/contacts.html |website=RAND Corporation |publisher=RAND Corporation |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSinek started Optimism Press,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://simonsinek.com/optimism-press/|title=Optimism Press|date=2019-06-19|website=Simon Sinek|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> which is an imprint of  [[Penguin Random House]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.ca/books/599282/how-to-make-a-plant-love-you-by-summer-rayne-oakes/9780525540281|title=How to Make a Plant Love You by Summer Rayne Oakes|website=Penguin Random House Canada|language=English|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nSinek became famous due to his TED TALKS speech on '[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u4ZoJKF_VuA Start with WHY'] which has been viewed by million of people and launched an entire new concept of infinite game.\n\n== '''THE GOLDEN CIRCLE THEORY''' ==\nThis is the concept introduced by Simon Sinek where he speaks about starting any business idea by asking the question of \"why is this thing done?\" or \"what is the purpose of doing this?\"  then \"How you are going to do it?\" and then \"what to do?\". He thinks this is the concept that has helped big companies like [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to outlast the competition. \n<br />\n==Books==\n*{{cite book|title=Start With Why: How Great Leaders Inspire Everyone to Take Action |url=https://archive.org/details/startwithwhyhowg00sine |url-access=registration |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2009 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591846444 |oclc=373054685}}\n*{{cite book |title=Leaders Eat Last: Why Some Teams Pull Together and Others Don't |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2014 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591845324 |oclc=818731578 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/leaderseatlastwh0000sine }}\n*{{cite book|title=Together Is Better: A Little Book of Inspiration |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2016 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591847854 |oclc=957455007}}<ref name=\"Forbes Sep 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danschawbel/2016/09/13/simon-sinek-why-you-need-other-people-in-order-to-build-a-successful-career|title=Simon Sinek: Why You Need Other People In Order To Build A Successful Career|last1=Schawbel|first1=Dan|date=Sep 13, 2016|accessdate=Jan 12, 2017|publisher=Forbes}}</ref>\n*{{cite book|title=Find Your Why: A Practical Guide for Discovering Purpose for You and Your Team |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2017 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=9781101992982 |oclc=963912431}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theladders.com/career-advice/millennials-listening-simon-sinek|title=Millennials are telling you why your company stinks but you're not listening: a Q&A with Simon Sinek|last=Burnett|first=Jane|date=August 23, 2017|work=Ladders|access-date=January 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*{{cite book|title=[[The Infinite Game]] |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=9780735213500 |oclc=1101645201}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinek, Simon}}\n[[Category:American motivational writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:People from Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:RAND Corporation people]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British/American author and motivational speaker}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image = simon sinek.jpg\n| imagesize = 225px\n| name = Simon Sinek\n| pseudonym = \n| caption = Sinek, TEDx Maastricht 2011\n| birth_name = Simon Oliver Sinek\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|10|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Wimbledon, London]], England\n| occupation = Author, [[motivational speaker]]\n| education = \n| alma_mater = City, University of London<br>Brandeis University\n| notableworks = ''[[Start With Why]]: How Great Leaders Inspire Everyone to Take Action'',''[[The Infinite Game]]''\n| years_active = \n| website = {{URL|https://simonsinek.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Simon Oliver Sinek''' (born October 9, 1973)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=gP0Fzj%2Fswk0Ugg9RqxkPXQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=19 July 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> is a British-born American author and [[motivational speaker]]. He is the author of five books, including ''[[Start With Why]]'' (2009)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkauflin/2017/06/20/the-years-5-bestselling-leadership-books-and-why-theyre-so-great/#257bb5043ac0|title=The Year's Five Bestselling Leadership Books, And Why They're So Great|last=Kauflin|first=Jeff|work=Forbes|access-date=January 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and ''[[The Infinite Game]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nSinek was born in [[Wimbledon, London]], United Kingdom and as a child lived in Johannesburg, South Africa, London, and Hong Kong before settling in the United States. He graduated from [[Northern Valley Regional High School at Demarest]] in 1991.<ref name=\"NorthernValleyRegionalHighSchool2013February11NVD\">{{cite web|last1=NVD|first1=|title=Simon Sinek Returns to NVD|url=http://www.nvnet.org/?plugin=RWD&Templates=RWD&object=/superintendents_blog/I074E94AE&infobar=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912182526/http://www.nvnet.org/?plugin=RWD&Templates=RWD&object=/superintendents_blog/I074E94AE&infobar=no |archive-date=12 September 2014 |url-status=dead|accessdate=28 January 2020|agency=NVD|publisher=Northern Valley Regional High School|date=11 February 2013|location=United States|language=English}}</ref> He studied law at London's [[City, University of London|City University]], but left law school to go into advertising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toolshero.com/toolsheroes/simon-sinek/|title=Simon Sinek biography, quotes and books|date=September 29, 2014}}</ref> He received a BA in [[cultural anthropology]] from [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://www.director.co.uk/opinion-simon-sinek-to-grow-your-business-let-go-20674-2/|title=Simon Sinek: To grow your business, let go|last1=Maxwell|first1=Chris|date=Jan 6, 2017|work=Director|accessdate=Jan 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSinek began his career at the New York ad agencies [[Havas Worldwide|Euro RSCG]] and [[Ogilvy & Mather]].<ref name=\"Director\" /> He later launched his own business, Sinek Partners.<ref name=\"Director\" />\n[[File:Golden circle.png|thumb|Simon Sinek's golden circle which describes a perspective of the influence of successful leaders and organisations.|alt=]]\nSinek has written five books. ''[[Start With Why]]'', his first book, was published October 2009. His second book, titled ''Leaders Eat Last'', appeared on the bestseller lists of the ''Wall Street Journal'' and ''The New York Times''.<ref name=\"Director\"/>   \n\nAs a motivational speaker, Sinek has given talks at [[United Nations Global Compact|The UN Global Compact]] Leaders Summit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unglobalcompact.org/take-action/events/leaders-summit/leaders-summit-programme|title=Programme {{!}} UN Global Compact|website=www.unglobalcompact.org|access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref> and at the [[TED_(conference)#TEDx|TEDx]] conference.<ref name=\"Entrepreneur\">{{cite news|last1=Koji|first1=David|title=An Inspiring Discussion With Simon Sinek About Learning Your 'Why'|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/284791|accessdate=2017-01-12|publisher=Entrepreneur|date=2016-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, ''[[The Young Turks]]'' reported a $98,000 no-bid contract from [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) for \"customized Simon Sinek leadership training\" to take place between April 26 and May 15 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tytnetwork.com/2018/06/26/ice-paid-famous-motivational-speaker-for-leadership-training/|title=ICE Paid Famous Motivational Speaker for 'Leadership Training'|website=tytnetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref>\n\nSinek is also an instructor of strategic communications at Columbia University,<ref>{{cite web |title=Instructor Simon Sinek Featured by 99% {{!}} Columbia University School of Professional Studies |url=http://sps.columbia.edu/strategic-communications/news/instructor-simon-sinek-featured-99 |website=sps.columbia.edu |language=en}}</ref> and is an adjunct staff member of the [[RAND Corporation]].<ref name=\"RAND\">{{cite web |title=RAND Corporation Staff Directory |url=https://www.rand.org/about/contacts.html |website=RAND Corporation |publisher=RAND Corporation |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSinek started Optimism Press,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://simonsinek.com/optimism-press/|title=Optimism Press|date=2019-06-19|website=Simon Sinek|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> which is an imprint of  [[Penguin Random House]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.ca/books/599282/how-to-make-a-plant-love-you-by-summer-rayne-oakes/9780525540281|title=How to Make a Plant Love You by Summer Rayne Oakes|website=Penguin Random House Canada|language=English|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book|title=Start With Why: How Great Leaders Inspire Everyone to Take Action |url=https://archive.org/details/startwithwhyhowg00sine |url-access=registration |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2009 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591846444 |oclc=373054685}}\n*{{cite book |title=Leaders Eat Last: Why Some Teams Pull Together and Others Don't |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2014 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591845324 |oclc=818731578 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/leaderseatlastwh0000sine }}\n*{{cite book|title=Together Is Better: A Little Book of Inspiration |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2016 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=978-1591847854 |oclc=957455007}}<ref name=\"Forbes Sep 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danschawbel/2016/09/13/simon-sinek-why-you-need-other-people-in-order-to-build-a-successful-career|title=Simon Sinek: Why You Need Other People In Order To Build A Successful Career|last1=Schawbel|first1=Dan|date=Sep 13, 2016|accessdate=Jan 12, 2017|publisher=Forbes}}</ref>\n*{{cite book|title=Find Your Why: A Practical Guide for Discovering Purpose for You and Your Team |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2017 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=9781101992982 |oclc=963912431}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theladders.com/career-advice/millennials-listening-simon-sinek|title=Millennials are telling you why your company stinks but you're not listening: a Q&A with Simon Sinek|last=Burnett|first=Jane|date=August 23, 2017|work=Ladders|access-date=January 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*{{cite book|title=[[The Infinite Game]] |last=Sinek |first=Simon |year=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Portfolio/Penguin |isbn=9780735213500 |oclc=1101645201}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinek, Simon}}\n[[Category:American motivational writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:People from Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:RAND Corporation people]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "Aswinee Pratihari", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have added some facts in his career part and describrd sortly about his  Golden Circle Theory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Sinek"}
